{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"4073a496-512b-4aa7-b1d1-8e74cbe894ae","content":"Run **`dotnet workload update`**. Here's why:\n\n| Command | What it does |\n|---|---|\n| `dotnet workload update` | Downloads and installs the **latest versions** of all installed workloads, matching them to your current SDK version. |\n| `dotnet workload repair` | **Re-installs** workloads at their current versions — useful if files are corrupted or missing, but won't pull newer versions. |\n\nAfter an SDK update, your workloads need versions that are **compatible with the new SDK**. `repair` would just reinstall the old (now-incompatible) versions.\n\n```bash\ndotnet workload update\n```\n\nIf the build still fails after that, run `dotnet workload list` to confirm the MAUI workload is installed, and check for any version mismatch warnings.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"e8451fef-774e-4205-85f1-2a997ccda2cf","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about the difference between `dotnet workload update` and `dotnet workload repair` to fix build issues after a .NET SDK update. This is a general knowledge question I can answer directly without needing to look at any files.","outputTokens":264,"requestId":"044E:14F244:ADC025:C6177C:6A027924"},"id":"885085d0-7081-4dcf-b3c4-095876210af6","timestamp":"2026-05-12T00:49:47.411Z","parentId":"4ff1db99-9fe1-433f-b0b6-517e50cdd5e4"}
